{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"de3695d2-3750-47c6-ae04-57d3c34dde63","content":"\n\nRun **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what brings workloads (like `maui`) back in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — reinstalls the **same versions** already recorded. It fixes corrupted or incomplete installs but won't pull newer packages needed by a newer SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:** SDK changed → `dotnet workload update`. Workload files got corrupted → `dotnet workload repair`.\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf you still get errors afterward, try a clean + rebuild (`dotnet clean && dotnet build`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b7dbed64-e7e6-401b-9515-cc4ab2274fc1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a knowledge question — I can answer directly without tools.","outputTokens":244},"id":"1a481739-234d-435f-bae7-8ac092b9aa8f","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:49:32.055Z","parentId":"88b62d15-6988-4b1a-93e0-3b3ed75a4d83"}
